 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=backwards7>backwards7</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/22/03 5:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  So who is going to rule in Heaven?</span><hr size=1> After finishing #42 with it's rather surprising cliff-hanger (I thought Garamas and Gyges were going to be a bit like Glob and Brute in The Sandman - easily dispatched) I wasn't sure how this arc fitted into the storyline.<br>
<br>
Now I understand, it's about Lucifer realising that if a pair of relatively stupid titans can cause this much trouble, then the position of God can't be left vacant. Someone has to sit on the throne of heaven, preferably someone who isn't going to cause him too many difficulties.<br>
<br>
I loved the page where Lucifer touches down in the silver city and the angels with their spears are a disorganised rabble. That panel of him slumped in Yahweh's throne with one foot up on the seat was pretty funny too.<br>
<br>
There's going to be quite a lot to wrap up in #44. I'm a bit confused as to what Lucifer means when he tells Michael that there are only three of us who can continue Yahweh's line.<br>
Does he mean Beatrice or could he be talking about Elaine Belloc? And what are those voices that follow Beatrice around - have I missed something?<br>
<br>
Obviously, whoever ends up ruling in heaven will play a role in the Morningstar's future. I wonder if in these next few issues we might see Lucifer sow the seeds of his own downfall. <br>
<br>
Maybe Yahweh departed the cosmos because it was the only way to restore order and have things return to their natural balance. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wulfenbach>wulfenbach</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/29/03 7:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  So who is going to rule in Heaven?</span><hr size=1> Of course he's talking about Elaine.  &quot;There are three of us who can continue Yahweh's line&quot; means three who are of Yahweh's line.  Michael, Lucifer, Elaine.  (Where'd the other angels come from?)  And Michael cares about Elaine to the point of defying God.  Where would Beatrice come into it?<br>
<br>
I wonder what would happen if Michael (or Elaine, if she's really like him she should have the demiurgic power, right?) destroys the throne, the Primum Mobile.  I presume we'll see if the Titans as &quot;God&quot; can resist that power.<br>
<br>
And what's their real status, anyway?  Really omnipotent, or just omnipotent relative to these creations?  And can Desire still tweak their hearts as usual?<br>
<br>
Two of the voices are the Titans; what they said in searching her memories was part of the voices from the bowling alley.  But in the doctor's office we get Lucifer and I think Beatrice and maybe someone else.  Hopefully the next issue will make things make sense. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 59<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/30/03 1:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: So who is going to rule in Heaven?</span><hr size=1> I would think, though, that the exercise of the demiurgic power would also have devastating effects on Yahweh's creation, unless Michael has the ability to mitigate his creative powers.<br>
<br>
I believe the creations of Yahweh, including the universe itself (and therefore by proxy The Endless) are not omnipotent.  Lucifer may be the only other entity (that we're aware of) who has experience omnipotence according to the creation of his own universe where he is presumably the supreme creator.  I've pondered whether this also implies that in his own creation he now has demiurgic power tantamount to Michael's, or if he is still limited in his abilities, which prompts the question: what defines power here?  The progenitor force?  Or the &quot;creation&quot; itself?  What is Yahweh outside the circle of infinity?<br>
<br>
I would suppose all of The Endless would still be able to impact the angels in various ways -- perhaps to lesser degrees than your average human -- so long as they remain subordinate to the creation itself. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#FFFF99>- </font><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer>Lucifer</a><font color=#FFFF99> - </font><a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1>Lucifer</a> <font color=#FFFF99> - </font><a href="http://lightbringer.mattpeckham.com/">Lightbringer: The Unofficial Lucifer Site</a><font color=#FFFF99> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.3e<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

